AB  - The term "Two-Spirit" refers to Indigenous individuals embodying both male and female spirits. Two-Spirit individuals perform the social roles of medicine healers, priests, and shamans, who conduct spiritual rituals, in traditional Indigenous ceremonies and practices. While a few researchers conceptualize Two-Spirit individuals as a distinct social group with their own unique history of colonial oppression, most have considered Two-Spirit persons to constitute a trans or sexual minority subgroup. Hence, the purpose of this paper is to provide a systematic review of Canadian research conducted specifically on Two-Spirit people and their communities. The findings were categorized into themes, such as historical focus, transition to modern ideas, contemporary meanings of Two-Spiritness, discriminatory experiences of Two-Spirit people, and the Two-Spirit narratives of resistance in Canada. Two-Spirit identity emerged as a complex terminology, depending on the unique traditions of Indigenous cultures and individuals' subjective experiences of identity development, discrimination from home communities and mainstream society, and resistance. The strengths and limitations of this review as well as future research implications are outlined.Alternate abstract:Le terme "bispirituel" fait reference aux individus autochtones aux esprits et feminin et masculin. Ces individus bispirituels assument les fonetions de guérisseur, de prétre et de chamane, effectuant des rituels spirituels au cours de ceremonies et de pratiques autochtones traditionnelles. Si quelques chercheurs voient en ces individus bispirituels les membres d'un groupe social distinct ayant subí le colonialismo autrement que d'autres autochtones, la plupart voient en ces individus les membres d'un groupe minoritaire défini par une minorisation de ľidentité sexuelle. Cet article a done pour but d'offrir un coup d'oeil systématique sur la recherche canadienne portant sur les bispirituels et leurs communautés. On 